# **INTELLIGENCE ANALYST**

## *Think Like an Investigator. Decide Like an Agency.*

---

## Game Overview

**Intelligence Analyst** is a single-player investigative puzzle game where the player works as an Intelligence Analyst inside one of the country's most secretive investigative agencies.

Unlike traditional detective games, you never chase suspects through the streets.

You never shoot anyone.

You never dust for fingerprints yourself.

You never physically visit crime scenes.

Instead...

**Every piece of evidence comes to you.**

Your job is to think.

Every decision you make determines whether justice is served...or the wrong person is arrested.

---

# The Story

You have just been recruited into the National Intelligence Analysis Bureau (NIAB), one of the most respected investigative organizations in the country.

Field investigators, police officers, forensic teams, banks, telecom companies, cybercrime units, prosecutors, and intelligence agents all gather evidence.

They send everything to one person...

**You.**

You're the analyst.

The person everyone depends on.

Without your analysis...

Cases collapse.

---

# Your Office

The entire game takes place inside your office.

Everything happens here.

This office is your headquarters.

Your workplace.

Your laboratory.

Your battlefield.

As your career grows...

Your office grows with you.

You begin with almost nothing.

One desk.

One computer.

One monitor.

A broken chair.

A small filing cabinet.

As promotions come...

Your office slowly transforms into one of the most advanced intelligence centers in the world.

---

# Career Progression

You don't simply unlock harder missions.

You build a career.

Promotions include:

* Trainee Investigator
* Junior Investigator
* Private Investigator
* Senior Investigator
* Lead Investigator
* Supervising Investigator
* Case Manager
* Operations Manager
* Agency Director
* Chief Investigator
* Regional Director
* Executive Director
* Managing Director
* Agency President
* Founder & Chairman

Every promotion introduces completely new investigation methods.

The hardest mission from one rank should feel easy compared to the easiest mission in the next.

---

# How Cases Arrive

Every morning your assistant enters your office.

> "Morning, Analyst."

She places today's case file on your desk.

Some days it's simple.

Some days it changes the country.

She explains the assignment.

She tells you the restrictions.

She tells you what the client expects.

Then she leaves.

Now...

It's your turn.

---

# Case File

Each case contains professionally organized evidence.

Examples include:

* Witness interviews
* CCTV photographs
* CCTV videos
* Phone records
* GPS history
* Financial transactions
* Bank statements
* Insurance claims
* Email conversations
* Chat logs
* Crime scene photographs
* Fingerprints
* DNA reports
* Autopsy reports
* Access card logs
* Vehicle tracking
* Security reports
* Satellite images
* Audio recordings
* Social media activity
* Business records
* Contracts
* Maps
* Time schedules
* Digital forensic reports

The evidence is rarely complete.

Some evidence is misleading.

Some evidence is fake.

Some evidence contradicts another.

Some evidence is missing.

Finding the truth is your responsibility.

---

# Investigation Process

You don't search for clues.

You analyze them.

Every case becomes a giant puzzle.

You compare documents.

Match timelines.

Study photographs.

Read statements.

Notice contradictions.

Connect seemingly unrelated events.

Discover hidden relationships.

Eventually...

A theory begins forming inside your head.

---

# Investigation Board

Every case includes an interactive analysis board.

Think of it as your detective wall.

You drag evidence.

Connect suspects.

Link locations.

Match timelines.

Highlight contradictions.

Organize theories.

Move documents around.

Cross-reference information.

When enough connections make sense...

The case begins solving itself.

---

# Question System

Throughout every investigation you'll answer investigation questions.

Examples:

Which witness is lying?

Who entered the building first?

Which phone belongs to the second suspect?

What happened between 9:17 PM and 9:26 PM?

Which transaction is suspicious?

Who had the strongest motive?

Which evidence is fabricated?

What sequence of events actually happened?

Each correct answer unlocks more evidence.

Wrong answers create problems.

---

# Multiple Ways To Lose

Unlike many puzzle games...

You can fail.

Examples:

Accuse the wrong suspect.

Ignore important evidence.

Trust fake evidence.

Miss the real timeline.

Overlook a contradiction.

Allow the criminal to escape.

Destroy your credibility.

Some missions also include restrictions.

Examples:

Solve without accusing innocent people.

Protect undercover agents.

Prevent information leaks.

Avoid unnecessary arrests.

Keep political pressure under control.

Protect witnesses.

Break the restrictions...

You fail.

---

# Performance Rating

Every case receives a professional evaluation.

Factors include:

Accuracy

Reasoning quality

Evidence usage

Time taken

Hints used

Collateral mistakes

Final report quality

Ranks range from:

Poor

Fair

Good

Excellent

Outstanding

Legendary Analysis

---

# Hints

Every investigation includes an assistant.

She never solves the case.

Instead...

She nudges you.

Hint 1

> "You should probably compare the bank statement with the timeline."

Hint 2

> "Someone's story doesn't match their phone location."

Hint 3

> "You're looking at the wrong suspect."

Hints never reveal answers.

They simply redirect your attention.

---

# Difficulty Progression

Cases evolve dramatically.

Early game:

One suspect.

Three witnesses.

Five pieces of evidence.

Simple theft.

Later:

Seven suspects.

Forty pieces of evidence.

Multiple fake clues.

Hidden financial fraud.

Corporate corruption.

International communications.

Cybercrime.

Money laundering.

Organized crime.

Government conspiracies.

The final missions feel like entire detective movies.

---

# Office Upgrades

Money earned from investigations can improve your office.

You begin with:

Old desk

Cheap chair

Single monitor

Tiny filing cabinet

Eventually you'll own:

Executive office

Evidence wall

Triple monitors

Digital investigation board

Cybercrime workstation

Satellite intelligence display

Forensic analysis terminal

DNA workstation

Secure archive

Financial crime terminal

International communication center

Command office

